So I did, I tried everything but ketamine (that was going to be next but the waiting list was six-eight weeks so I decided to go with ECT instead) and I’m glad I finally reached this point because it seems to be really working for me.

I’ve been inpatient, I’ve done two partial hospitalization programs, one intensive outpatient program, TMS, biofeedback, crystals, meditation, CBT, ACT...you get the point. I wanted to try every single thing before #ECT even though it had been recommended to me years ago.

This comes and goes and has morphed back and forth along the way because I also suffer from #bipolarII but my ups haven’t reach hypomania in years and my downs have been so much worse. I’ve tried so many things; almost every drug, switched docs & therapists a couple of times...

I’ve been seriously, severely depressed for 5 1/2 years after health problems caused me to lose my job. I’ve had agoraphobic tendencies, suicidal thoughts, self care has been impossible, being awake made me feel itchy at times so I couldn’t stand being awake. #depression

Obviously this is a big decision and everyone’s different, you may have more or far worse side effects and/or  may not feel results as quickly, so I’m not recommending everyone go get #ECT. I’m just saying that my experience thus far has been great after being scared for so long.

I thought it might be the magic feather effect but on Monday they did ask if I felt any benefits, after just one session, so I think this is legit. I have been kicking ass; exercising, running errands, doing laundry, etc. I’m not out of the woods yet of course but I am on my way.

I shouldn’t look backwards but I wish I’d started #ECT four years ago. I was so terrified of it until my first treatment ended on Friday. I woke up and felt fine. I was afraid I’d be a zombie or something but nope. I’ve only had two sessions and I am already seeing improvements.

I am not used to this new chill, get stuff done hypomania but as I look back on the past four months that’s exactly what’s been going on. I have gotten so much done and I always think it’s because I’m getting better but I’m not. It must be that my hypomania’s morphed again.

Tunnel vision or hyperfocus (I also have ADD) is a gift and a curse. Sometimes you get very important things done but usually at the expense of some other area that needed your attention. And then there are times when you hyperfocus on dissecting Joe vs The Volcano (true story).

Then it became “I need to fix this area of my life and everything will be fine.” I got so much shit done but with the tunnel vision still in effect I’d miss work to scrub the grout on the bathroom floor with a toothbrush because nothing felt more important.

I started with textbook hypomania (spending more money than I had because “you have to experience life”, etc.). Then it became tunnel vision obsession on an area. Saving the planet for instance, I quit smoking because I was very hypomanic so don’t say it never did nothing for me.

Maybe my hypomania just now feels like, “hey I’m getting some stuff done, maybe the meds are working.” And then the inevitable crash comes and I’m back to not being able to stomach being awake. I’m still going up and down just not nearly as up as I am down. Does that make sense?

Depression has ups and downs obviously but mine are definitely more akin to low grade hypomania. It has been getting less and less severe as I age. Maybe my hypomania is now just showering three times in a week as opposed to day and night like it used to be. Just an example.

I have bipolar II. I’m not ashamed to admit it but I usually only mention depression because I haven’t had true hypomania in so long. I realized recently that even though my highs aren’t as high I am used to I am definitely riding the bipolar coaster

Tell people how hard living will be not about dying.

Telling people who aren’t particularly afraid of dying that something is going to eventually kill them is not an effective message.

It did not work on me when it came to smoking. I didn’t quit because I was afraid of five years being lopped off the end of my life.

No fat shaming here, this is solely about myself. Everyone has different experiences and may not go through what I’m going through.

I was just taken aback by the assumption that the reason to eat well is to not die but the more important reason to eat well is to live well.

I may also happen to die earlier than I would have if I hadn’t had an eating disorder or had gotten it under control years ago but dying is in no way the worst part IMO.

Living like this sucks. I’m in so much pain and I can’t get around easily and I can’t find clothes.

I was just “nagging” my daughter about nutrition and she said, “whatever if I die, I’ll die happy!”

It isn’t about dying though, it’s about living.
